Acknowledge (verb)
To recognize or admit the existence or truth of something.
"The researcher acknowledged the limitations of the study."

2. Bias (noun)
An unfair preference or prejudice that affects judgment.
"The survey results showed a clear bias toward urban respondents."

3. Contradict (verb)
To say or show the opposite of something.
"The new evidence contradicted the original theory."

4. Derive (verb)
To obtain or develop something from a source.
"Many English words are derived from Latin roots."

5. Hypothesis (noun)
A proposed explanation made as a starting point for investigation.
"The team tested their hypothesis through a series of experiments."

6. Inevitable (adjective)
Certain to happen; unable to be avoided.
"Change is an inevitable part of scientific progress."

7. Modify (verb)
To make partial changes to something; to adjust.
"The professor asked students to modify their thesis statements."

8. Perceive (verb)
To become aware of something through the senses or the mind.
"How we perceive information affects how we understand it."

9. Relevant (adjective)
Closely connected or appropriate to the topic at hand.
"Only relevant sources should be cited in academic writing."

10. Substantial (adjective)
Of considerable importance, size, or worth.
"There is substantial evidence supporting this conclusion."

